If you reference to that plugin dll it's possible. But in that case it's not a plugin anymore, it becomes a development time dependency.

If you want to do without referencing it, you can make that:

Inject ``IAbpModuleManager`` into your main module that should check the plugin existence. Then use it's ``Modules`` collection to get list of all loaded modules. Thus, you can check if your module does exists. You can use such a code to avoid hard referencing:

````C#
if(_moduleManager.Modules.Any(m => m.Type.Name == "MyPlugInModule"))
{
    ....
}
````

